<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1946-04-25T09:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1946-04-25T09:00:00-05:00" n="372" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d372">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 PW/4–2546: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Smith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left"><hi rend="smallcaps">restricted</hi></seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1946-04-25T17:00:00+03:00">April 25, 1946—5
                                p.m.</date><lb/>[Received April 26—12:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1343. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss>s 1306 and 1307, April
                                23.<note n="9" xml:id="d372fn1">For telegram 1307, see <ref target="frus1946v10#pg_1122"><hi rend="italic">Foreign
                                        Relations</hi>, 1946, vol. <hi rend="smallcaps">x</hi>, p.
                                    1122</ref>.</note> Replying to British note of March 9 on
                            removal of <gloss target="#t_Jap1">Jap</gloss> assets in Manchuria
                            Vyshinski <pb facs="0505" n="493" xml:id="pg_493"/> made additional
                            statement not included in his reply to our similar notes as follows:
                                <quote rend="blockquote">
                                <p>“Insofar as Japanese assets belonging to the category of military
                                    trophies are concerned the Soviet Govt is unable to agree with
                                    the British Govt’s view that these assets should be debited
                                    against the eventual share of Japanese reparations of the state
                                    in whose territory such assets are located.[”]</p>
                            </quote></p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Smith</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>